<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
	ws-gradient.ptx
	Section 1 (Functions, Vectors, and Vector Fields), worksheet 6:
	The Gradient and Directional Derivatives.

	Ported from the Beamer deck 01_05_Gradient.tex (in
	source/notes/latex/, functions-vectors folder): scalar functions, the
	gradient, the directional derivative, and the direction of steepest
	ascent / maximum rate of change. Book concepts tracked from
	sec_partial_derivatives / sec_directional_derivative; example
	equations are NOT reused from the deck or the book.

	Authored to the SHARED worksheet conventions
	(checklists/worksheet-conventions.md): paired component="stu"/"key"
	reading checks and exercises; one True/False misconception check; one
	read-along TikZ figure; one modern application. Standard notation
	(macros from source/bookends/docinfo.ptx); no new macros. Math-valued
	answer keys are underlined directly (\underline{...}); only plain-word
	answers are bolded, so the pdf-key (LaTeX) build stays clean.
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-gradient">
	<title>The Gradient and Directional Derivatives</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li>Compute the gradient <m>\nabla f</m> of a scalar function of two or three variables.</li>
			<li>Compute the directional derivative <m>D_{\vu} f = \nabla f \cdot \vu</m> using a <em>unit</em> vector <m>\vu</m>.</li>
			<li>Use the gradient to find the direction of steepest ascent and the maximum rate of change <m>\norm{\nabla f}</m>.</li>
			<li>Explain why <m>f</m> cannot change faster than <m>\norm{\nabla f}</m> in any direction.</li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 1: The gradient
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>I. The gradient.</term></p>

		<p>
			A <term>scalar function</term> such as <m>f(x,y)</m> or
			<m>g(x,y,z)</m> returns a single number. Its <term>gradient</term>
			collects the partial derivatives into a vector:
			<md>
				\nabla f = [\,f_x,\; f_y\,], \qquad
				\nabla g = [\,g_x,\; g_y,\; g_z\,].
			</md>
			The gradient is itself a vector that varies from point to point
			<ndash/> a first example of a <term>vector field</term>.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 1 -->
		<p component="stu">
			The gradient of <m>f(x,y)</m> is <m>\nabla f = [\,</m>
			<fillin characters="4"/> <m>,\;</m> <fillin characters="4"/>
			<m>\,]</m>, a <fillin characters="7"/> <nbsp/>whose components are
			the first partial derivatives of <m>f</m>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			The gradient of <m>f(x,y)</m> is
			<m>\nabla f = [\,\underline{f_x},\; \underline{f_y}\,]</m>, a
			<m>\underline{\textbf{vector}}</m> whose components are the first
			partial derivatives of <m>f</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>f(x,y) = x^2 y + 3y</m>. Find <m>\nabla f</m> and
					evaluate it at <m>P(1,2)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>f(x,y) = x^2 y + 3y</m>. Find <m>\nabla f</m> and
					evaluate it at <m>P(1,2)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					The partials are <m>f_x = 2xy</m> and <m>f_y = x^2 + 3</m>, so
					<md>
						\nabla f = [\,2xy,\; x^2+3\,],
						\qquad \nabla f(1,2) = [\,2(1)(2),\; 1+3\,] = [\,4,\;4\,].
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>Your turn.</term></p>

		<!-- practice problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>g(x,y,z) = x^2 + yz + z^2</m>. Find <m>\nabla g</m> and
					evaluate it at <m>P(2,1,-1)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>g(x,y,z) = x^2 + yz + z^2</m>. Find <m>\nabla g</m> and
					evaluate it at <m>P(2,1,-1)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Here <m>g_x = 2x</m>, <m>g_y = z</m>, and
					<m>g_z = y + 2z</m>, so
					<md>
						\nabla g = [\,2x,\; z,\; y+2z\,],
						\qquad \nabla g(2,1,-1) = [\,4,\; -1,\; 1+2(-1)\,] = [\,4,\;-1,\;-1\,].
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 2: The directional derivative
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>II. The directional derivative.</term></p>

		<p>
			The rate at which <m>f</m> changes as you move from a point in the
			direction of a <em>unit</em> vector <m>\vu</m> is the
			<term>directional derivative</term>
			<md>
				D_{\vu} f = \nabla f \cdot \vu .
			</md>
			The unit-vector requirement is essential. If a direction is handed
			to you as a vector <m>\vv</m> that is not a unit vector, first
			rescale it: <m>\vu = \vv/\norm{\vv}</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 2 -->
		<p component="stu">
			The directional derivative of <m>f</m> in the direction of a unit
			vector <m>\vu</m> is <m>D_{\vu} f = </m> <fillin characters="7"/>.
			If the direction is given as a vector <m>\vv</m> that is not a unit
			vector, first replace it with <m>\vu = </m> <fillin characters="7"/>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			The directional derivative of <m>f</m> in the direction of a unit
			vector <m>\vu</m> is
			<m>D_{\vu} f = \underline{\nabla f \cdot \vu}</m>. If the direction
			is given as a vector <m>\vv</m> that is not a unit vector, first
			replace it with <m>\vu = \underline{\vv/\norm{\vv}}</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>h(x,y) = x^2 + xy</m>. Find the directional derivative
					of <m>h</m> at <m>P(1,2)</m> in the direction of
					<m>\vv = [\,3,\,4\,]</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>h(x,y) = x^2 + xy</m>. Find the directional derivative
					of <m>h</m> at <m>P(1,2)</m> in the direction of
					<m>\vv = [\,3,\,4\,]</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					First the gradient:
					<m>\nabla h = [\,2x+y,\; x\,]</m>, so
					<m>\nabla h(1,2) = [\,4,\;1\,]</m>. Since
					<m>\norm{\vv} = \sqrt{3^2+4^2} = 5</m>, the unit direction is
					<m>\vu = \vv/\norm{\vv} = [\,3/5,\;4/5\,]</m>. Therefore
					<md>
						D_{\vu} h(P) = \nabla h(1,2)\cdot \vu
						= [\,4,\,1\,]\cdot[\,3/5,\,4/5\,]
						= \frac{12 + 4}{5} = \frac{16}{5}.
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 3: Steepest ascent and the maximum rate
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>III. Steepest ascent and the maximum rate.</term></p>

		<p>
			Because <m>\vu</m> is a unit vector,
			<md>
				D_{\vu} f = \nabla f \cdot \vu
				= \norm{\nabla f}\,\norm{\vu}\cos\theta
				= \norm{\nabla f}\cos\theta,
			</md>
			where <m>\theta</m> is the angle between <m>\vu</m> and
			<m>\nabla f</m>. This is largest when <m>\theta = 0</m>, i.e. when
			<m>\vu</m> points along <m>\nabla f</m>. So <m>\nabla f</m> points
			in the direction of steepest ascent, and the greatest rate of
			increase equals <m>\norm{\nabla f}</m>. The gradient is also
			perpendicular to the level curves of <m>f</m>.
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="ws-gradient-fig-level">
			<caption>The gradient <m>\nabla f</m> is perpendicular to the level
				curves of <m>f</m> and points toward higher values <ndash/> the
				direction of steepest ascent.</caption>
			<image width="52%">
				<shortdescription>Three nested closed level curves of a scalar function, higher toward the center, with the gradient vector drawn at a point on the middle curve, perpendicular to it and pointing inward toward the higher curves.</shortdescription>
				<latex-image>
	\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.05,>=stealth]
	% nested level curves of a hill (higher toward the center)
	\draw[gray] (0,0) ellipse (2.4 and 1.7);
	\draw[gray] (0,0) ellipse (1.6 and 1.13);
	\draw[gray] (0,0) ellipse (0.8 and 0.57);
	\node[gray, font=\footnotesize] at (0,0) {higher $f$};
	\node[gray, font=\footnotesize, anchor=west] at (2.45,-0.05) {$f=1$};
	\node[gray, font=\footnotesize, anchor=west] at (1.65,0.35) {$f=2$};
	% point P on the middle level curve
	\coordinate (P) at (1.6,0);
	\fill (P) circle (1.6pt);
	\node[anchor=south west] at (P) {$P$};
	% gradient at P: perpendicular to the curve, pointing inward (uphill)
	\draw[very thick, red, ->] (P) -- (0.75,0);
	\node[red, anchor=south] at (1.2,0.08) {$\nabla f$};
	\end{tikzpicture}
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<!-- reading-check pair 3 -->
		<p component="stu">
			The function <m>f</m> increases fastest in the direction of
			<fillin characters="6"/>, and that maximum rate of increase equals
			<fillin characters="8"/>. In every direction the rate of change lies
			between <fillin characters="10"/> <nbsp/>and <m>\norm{\nabla f}</m>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			The function <m>f</m> increases fastest in the direction of
			<m>\underline{\nabla f}</m>, and that maximum rate of increase equals
			<m>\underline{\norm{\nabla f}}</m>. In every direction the rate of
			change lies between <m>\underline{-\norm{\nabla f}}</m> and
			<m>\norm{\nabla f}</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					For <m>h(x,y) = x^2 + xy</m> at <m>P(1,2)</m> (same gradient as
					before), in which direction does <m>h</m> increase fastest, and
					what is that maximum rate of increase?
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					For <m>h(x,y) = x^2 + xy</m> at <m>P(1,2)</m> (same gradient as
					before), in which direction does <m>h</m> increase fastest, and
					what is that maximum rate of increase?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					We found <m>\nabla h(1,2) = [\,4,\,1\,]</m>. The fastest
					increase is in the direction of the gradient itself, i.e. the
					unit vector
					<md>
						\vu = \frac{\nabla h(P)}{\norm{\nabla h(P)}}
						= \frac{[\,4,\,1\,]}{\sqrt{17}},
					</md>
					and the maximum rate of increase is
					<m>\norm{\nabla h(P)} = \sqrt{4^2 + 1^2} = \sqrt{17}</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 4: A misconception, an application, and looking ahead
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>IV. A caution and an application.</term></p>

		<!-- misconception check: single exercise, solution instructor-only -->
		<exercise xml:id="ws-gradient-tf-unit">
			<statement>
				<p>
					<alert>True or False.</alert> To find the directional derivative
					of <m>f</m> in the direction of <m>\vv = [\,3,\,4\,]</m>, you
					compute <m>\nabla f \cdot [\,3,\,4\,]</m>. Explain.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					<term>False.</term> The formula <m>D_{\vu} f = \nabla f\cdot\vu</m>
					requires a <em>unit</em> vector. Here
					<m>\norm{\vv} = 5 \neq 1</m>, so you must first normalize:
					<m>\vu = [\,3/5,\,4/5\,]</m> and
					<m>D_{\vu} f = \nabla f\cdot[\,3/5,\,4/5\,]</m>. Using the raw
					<m>[\,3,\,4\,]</m> overstates the rate by a factor of
					<m>\norm{\vv} = 5</m>. (Forgetting to normalize is the most
					common directional-derivative error.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>An application.</term></p>

		<!-- application (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A hill has height <m>H(x,y) = 20 - x^2 - 2y^2</m> meters above
					the point <m>(x,y)</m> on the ground. A hiker stands above
					<m>P(1,1)</m>.
					<ol>
						<li>Which compass direction is steepest uphill, and how steep is it there (rate of rise per unit of horizontal travel)?</li>
						<li>Is there any direction in which the ground rises at a rate of <m>5</m>? Why or why not?</li>
					</ol>
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A hill has height <m>H(x,y) = 20 - x^2 - 2y^2</m> meters above
					the point <m>(x,y)</m> on the ground. A hiker stands above
					<m>P(1,1)</m>.
					<ol>
						<li>Which compass direction is steepest uphill, and how steep is it there (rate of rise per unit of horizontal travel)?</li>
						<li>Is there any direction in which the ground rises at a rate of <m>5</m>? Why or why not?</li>
					</ol>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<ol>
						<li>
							<m>\nabla H = [\,-2x,\; -4y\,]</m>, so
							<m>\nabla H(1,1) = [\,-2,\,-4\,]</m>. The steepest uphill
							direction is the gradient, i.e. the unit vector
							<m>\vu = [\,-2,\,-4\,]/\sqrt{20} = [\,-1,\,-2\,]/\sqrt{5}</m>
							(pointing back toward the summit), and the slope there is
							<m>\norm{\nabla H(P)} = \sqrt{(-2)^2+(-4)^2} = \sqrt{20} = 2\sqrt5 \approx 4.47</m>.
						</li>
						<li>
							No. The rate of change in <em>any</em> direction lies
							between <m>-\norm{\nabla H(P)}</m> and
							<m>\norm{\nabla H(P)} = 2\sqrt5 \approx 4.47</m>. Since
							<m>5 &gt; 2\sqrt5</m>, no direction achieves a rate of
							<m>5</m>.
						</li>
					</ol>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<conclusion>
			<p>
				<alert>Looking ahead.</alert> The gradient turned a scalar
				function into a <term>vector field</term> <ndash/> a vector
				attached to every point. That is exactly the object the rest of
				vector analysis studies: next we meet vector fields in their own
				right, and then learn to integrate along curves through them, the
				<term>line integrals</term> that open Section 2.
			</p>
		</conclusion>
	</page>

</worksheet>
